lead_paragraph: An obituary Friday about Sir Edmund Hillary, who with Tenzing Norgay became the first to scale Mount Everest, misidentified the route they took to the summit. It is the South Col, not the South Tor. In comparing the feat to one by Charles A. Lindbergh, the obituary misstated Lindbergh’s accomplishment. Though he was the first to make a solo nonstop trans-Atlantic flight, in 1927, he was not the first aviator to make the nonstop crossing; John W. Alcock and Arthur W. Brown did so together in 1919, from Newfoundland to Ireland. In addition, the precedents for Sir Edmund’s reaching the South Pole in 1957-58 were referred to incorrectly. Robert Falcon Scott reached the pole in 1912, and the United States built a base there in 1956; Sir Edmund was not the first to reach the pole since Roald Amundsen in 1911.

lead_paragraph: KUCZYNSKI--Dr. H. June (Jadwiga) of Bloomfield Hills, MI passed away on January 31, 2008. Beloved wife of Edward for 52 years. Loving mother of Yvonne Sesi (Joe), Ed, and Barbara. Adoring grandmother of Eddie Kuczynski and Katie Sesi. Born in Wilno, Poland on February 20, 1929 she was deported as a child to a Siberian labor camp by the Soviet Union during World War II. Her family eventually settled in Tanzania, Africa, where she completed high school. Subsequently, she emigrated to England, where she completed her nursing and midwifery training. In 1957, June and her new husband arrived in the United States on the Queen Mary. June continued her nursing education, earning a Doctor of Philosophy from Wayne State University in Detroit, MI. Dr. Kuczynski was tenured faculty in the School of Nursing at Wayne State University for almost 30 years. She received many accolades and awards including The President's Award for Excellence in Teaching. Cardinal Karol Wojtyla (the future Pope John Paul II) visited her home in 1977. She has been to the White House on numerous occasions. Her warm smile and kind heart will be missed by family, friends and her dear students. lead_paragraph: STERN--Eli, 96, on February 11, 2008. Mr. Stern prepared this obituary himself some time ago: I dearly loved my wife Ruth of 67 years, my daughter Sheila, and my grandsons Adam and Gabriel Many. I enjoyed being a painter and sculptor, writing poetry, and woodworking. I was happy to be active in the Workmen's Circle and to write and prepare the monthly bulletin of my Penn South Branch 1076 for many years. I enjoyed conducting a discussion group at the Penn South Program for Seniors. One of my life's greatest satisfactions was attending New York City's John Jay College after I retired, graduating summa cum laude at age 68. I enjoyed the flowers and vegetables I grew on my apartment balcony. I enjoyed playing bridge, Scrabble and other games. From my youth onward I was a believer in democratic socialism and cooperation. I was always curious about everything. On the whole, life was good.

lead_paragraph: PETERSON--Vera Joseph, died peacefully Saturday, January 26, 2008, in Springfield, Massachusetts. She was 98. Born in a small village in St. Ann's Parish, Jamaica, WI, Dr. Joseph, as she was known professionally, came to the United States through Ellis Island in 1919. She attended George Washington High School in New York City and won a scholarship to Barnard. She was one of the first African-American graduates of Barnard College where she earned Phi Beta Kappa as a junior and graduated in 1932. Dr. Joseph earned her medical school degree at the College of Physicians & Surgeons at Columbia University graduating AOA in 1936. She subsequently did an internship at Harlem Hospital. In 1938, she married Dr. Jerome S. Peterson, also a graduate of Columbia University Physicians & Surgeons graduate of 1931. From 1940 to 1942, they lived in Puerto Rico where they managed several tuberculosis clinics. Returning to New York, Dr. Joseph was a physician and assistant to the director at the International Ladies Garment Workers Union Health Center. In 1950 the family moved to Beirut, Lebanon, where Dr. Joseph was an assistant professor of medicine at the American University of Beirut while her husband worked with the United Nations. The family relocated to Geneva, Switzerland, in 1953 when her husband accepted a position with the World Health Organization. In Geneva, Dr. Joseph was active with the Medical Women's International Association and served as its honorary secretary. She was a member of the Governing Board of the International School, and in 1958 became consultant to the European regional Office of WHO for the advisory group on public health and aging. The couple returned to the United States in 1964, settling in Amherst, Massachusetts. Dr. Joseph assumed a position with the Smith College Health Service, where she eventually rose to become Director. In 1974 she and her husband were co-recipients of the Ira Hiscock award for contributions in public health from the New England Public Health Association. She retired in 1975 from Smith College Health Service. Dr. Joseph served as a Trustee of the Jones Library and the Amherst Savings Bank, Board of Overseers of Williston-Northampton School and on the Health Services Advisory Council of the College of Physicians & Surgeons. Her husband died in 1987, and she founded the Vera Joseph/Jerome S. Peterson Fund for Minority Students at the College of Physicians & Surgeons to honor his memory. Dr. Joseph eventually moved from Amherst to Reeds Landing, a retirement community in Springfield. Vera Joseph Peterson is survived by three daughters; Jane Peterson of Seattle, Washington, Danna Peterson of Worcester, Massachusetts, and Carla Rosenbloom of Washington, D.C., four grandchildren; Claire Roberts of Spokane, Washington, Sarah Rosenbloom of New York City, Julia Rosenbloom of Philadelphia, and Philip Peterson of Worcester, and one greatgrandchild, Jacob Roberts of Spokane. A Memorial Mass will be held on Friday, February 1, at 11:00am in St. Brigid's Church in Amherst. Burial will follow in Wildwood Cemetery. Obituary and register at: douglassfuneral.com

lead_paragraph: A front-page article on Jan. 26 about the growing endowments of college preparatory schools referred incorrectly to the rankings by age of prep schools in the United States, and a correction in this space on Saturday misstated the founding date of one of those schools. Phillips Exeter Academy in Exeter, N.H., is the sixth-oldest boarding school, not the third-oldest school over all, including day schools. And Phillips Academy in Andover, Mass., was founded in 1778, not 1781. An accompanying article about prep schools’ hiring of professionals to invest endowments and run capital campaigns misstated the given name and the surname of a New York consultant who helped the Children’s School in Stamford, Conn., raise $7 million. He is Timothy L. Hogen, not Tom Hogan.
